Reference: https://www.int-res.com/abstracts/meps/v126/p9-17/
Notes: Juveniles spend time foraging in intertidal (relevance to fisheries and ecosystem services); "There were few differences in pollock densities between algal and open habitats but abundances likely increased in the algal habitat at higher tidal stages when changes in habitat availability are taken into account. Densities were higher at night and there was an order of magnitude decline in pollock densities from early to late summer. In another study we showed that piscivorous birds are a probable cause of pollock summer mortality. Pollock fed on invertebrates from intertidal algae relatively continuously."
